This paper deals with the problem of planar pushing and grasping, which is a common topic in robotics research. The paper proposes a new contact model that is fast and stochastic, which is relevant to the field of robotics. The paper also validates the model through robotic pushing and grasping experiments, which suggests that it is likely to be submitted to the Robotics (cs.RO) sub-category. Additionally, the paper uses physically consistent parameters and simulations, which suggests that it may also be relevant to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The paper also uses computer vision techniques to determine the contact modes and object motion, which suggests that it may be relevant to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category. The paper also deals with the mechanics of patch contact, which suggests that it may be relevant to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category. Finally, the paper uses stochastic models and simulations, which suggests that it may be relevant to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category.
